---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import ExternalLink from "@/components/ExternalLink.astro";
import StatusBadge from "@/components/StatusBadge.astro";
import TagList from "@/components/TagList.astro";
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const project = (await getCollection("projects")).find(
  (entry) => entry.data.slug === "the-human-model",
);
if (!project) {
  throw new Error("Missing The Human Model project entry");
}
---

<BaseLayout
  title={project.data.title}
  description={project.data.summary}
  canonicalPath="/projects/the-human-model/"
>
  <section class="page-section container text-page">
    <p class="eyebrow">Flagship project</p>
    <h1>{project.data.title}</h1>
    <p class="lede">{project.data.summary}</p>
    <div class="button-row">
      <StatusBadge status={project.data.status} accent={project.data.accent} />
      {
        project.data.repositoryUrl && (
          <ExternalLink href={project.data.repositoryUrl} label="Repository" />
        )
      }
    </div>
    <TagList tags={project.data.tags} />

    <h2>Project introduction</h2>
    <p>
      The Human Model is a personal research platform for understanding human
      performance through data, biomechanics, and adaptive systems.
    </p>
    <p>
      It combines wearable data, training logs, conversational input,
      biomechanics, and machine learning into a continuously evolving model of a
      person. The core loop is: Measure -> Model -> Reason -> Adapt.
    </p>

    <h2>Why it exists</h2>
    <p>
      I am interested in what happens when human performance is treated as a
      dynamic system rather than a collection of isolated metrics. Sleep
      influences recovery. Recovery influences training. Training drives
      adaptation. Adaptation changes future performance. Every decision creates
      new information that influences the next.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most current tools measure parts of that process well. They can tell us
      how we slept, how hard we trained, or how recovered we might be. But they
      rarely attempt to understand how those signals interact over time, or what
      those interactions mean for future performance.
    </p>
    <p class="callout">
      The goal is not simply to collect more data. It is to build a better
      understanding of how people adapt over time.
    </p>

    <h2>The feedback loop</h2>
    <div class="diagram loop" aria-label="Measure, model, reason, adapt loop">
      <div class="diagram-row">
        <div class="diagram-node">Measure</div>
        <div class="diagram-node">Model</div>
        <div class="diagram-node">Reason</div>
        <div class="diagram-node">Adapt</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      Most fitness tools stop at measurement. The Human Model asks what comes
      next: how a system can turn scattered signals into structured evidence,
      use that evidence to reason, and then learn from the next action.
    </p>

    <h2>Current systems</h2>
    <div class="status-grid">
      <section>
        <h3>Bridget</h3>
        <p>
          Bridget captures conversations, observations, and context that numbers
          miss, turning everyday interactions into structured evidence the Human
          Model can learn from.
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h3>Decision Support Dashboard</h3>
        <p>
          The dashboard brings recovery, training, body measurements, and system
          health together in one place. It helps surface patterns, support
          better questions, and decide what to try next.
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h3>Predictive Models</h3>
        <p>
          The predictive-modeling work explores whether past training and
          recovery can help predict what comes next, turning historical data
          into hypotheses that can be tested in the real world.
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h3>Computer Vision</h3>
        <p>
          The computer-vision work transforms training videos into measurable
          movement data. It explores how technique, consistency, fatigue, and
          adaptation change over time.
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h3>Experimental Hardware</h3>
        <p>
          The hardware work experiments with ways to measure human performance
          beyond today's wearables and explores which additional signals might
          make the Human Model more complete.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <h2>What makes it different</h2>
    <p>
      The Human Model is not only a fitness tracker or dashboard. It combines
      objective measurements, subjective observations, conversational context,
      historical behavior, biomechanics, and changing goals.
    </p>
    <p>
      The larger exploration is how software can reason about human performance
      as a changing system: what it knows, what it is guessing, what evidence is
      missing, and what decision should be tested next.
    </p>

    <h2>Current status</h2>
    <ul class="quiet-list split-list">
      <li>Active personal research platform</li>
      <li>Experimental modeling and interface work</li>
      <li>Building in public through docs, examples, and public summaries</li>
      <li>Not a finished product or generalized coaching system</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Links</h2>
    <div class="button-row">
      {
        project.data.repositoryUrl && (
          <ExternalLink
            href={project.data.repositoryUrl}
            label="Human Model repository"
          />
        )
      }
      <ExternalLink
        href="https://github.com/haleyparks329/the-human-model/tree/main/examples"
        label="Public examples"
      />
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .callout {
    border-left: 5px solid var(--rust);
    padding: 1rem 0 1rem 1.2rem;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-weight: 800;
  }

  .status-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  .status-grid section {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(247, 236, 212, 0.66);
  }

  @media (max-width: 820px) {
    .status-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }

  .loop .diagram-row {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, minmax(0, 1fr));
  }

  @media (max-width: 820px) {
    .loop .diagram-row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
